	<div class="blog-archive-entries-wrapper">
		<div id="unique-entry-id-415" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Pirate Quiz</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Friday, 03 June 2011 </div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="jolly roger" src="jollyroger.jpg" width="40" height="39" /></div>We are off to collect today&rsquo;s Times after reading this from @JustinSomper on twitter.<br />Check out a swashbuckling pirate quiz by yours truly in today's Times (Young Times). Which pirate are you?<br /></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-413" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Seven Stories Pirate Week</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Saturday, 28 May 2011 </div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="jolly roger" src="jollyroger.jpg" width="40" height="39" /></div>Are you in Newcastle Upon Tyne near Ouseburn Valley.  Well Seven Stories on Lime Street has Pirate Week this Spring Half Term.  Please see http://www.sevenstories.org.uk/whats-on/pirate-week-this-spring-half-term-e48909 for more details.<br /></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-393" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Red Nose Day</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Friday, 18 March 2011 </div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="Captain Conk" src="Sq_RND.jpg" width="40" height="40" /></div>Did you get to dress up today?  My kids and most of the school were pirates so I am sure there were loads of 'Pirate Academy' schools in the United kingdom today full of pirates<br /><br />For anyone who does not know Comic Relief has announced the next Red Nose Day will be 18th March 2011 and one of the noses they have released is Captain Conk the pirate.  Every two years the UK comedians help raise money to help make a difference to peoples lives both in the UK and abroad (predominantly in Africa).  So for the &pound;1 spent to buy either a Captain Conk red nose from Sainsbury's or Captain Conk pen from Ryman's, half of the profits goes to UK and half to Africa.  (Just a note on the nose boxes it says "with at least 70p going to Comic Relief" and the pens have "Ryman will donate &pound;1 for each pen sold.")<br />Please see <a href="http://www.rednoseday.com/" rel="self" title="http://www.rednoseday.com/">http://www.rednoseday.com/</a> for more information.<br /><br /></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-389" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Charities</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Wednesday, 16 February 2011 </div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="Captain Conk" src="Sq_RND.jpg" width="40" height="40" /></div>I have heard recently of two charities that might interest you.<br /><br />The first is a UK one with a pirate.  For anyone who does not know Comic Relief has announced the next Red Nose Day will be 18th March 2011 and one of the noses they have released is Captain Conk the pirate.  Every two years the UK comedians help raise money to help make a difference to peoples lives both in the UK and abroad (predominantly in Africa).  So for the &pound;1 spent to buy either a Captain Conk red nose from Sainsbury's or Captain Conk pen from Ryman's, half of the profits goes to UK and half to Africa.  (Just a note on the nose boxes it says "with at least 70p going to Comic Relief" and the pens have "Ryman will donate &pound;1 for each pen sold.")<br />Please see <a href="http://www.rednoseday.com/" rel="self" title="http://www.rednoseday.com/">http://www.rednoseday.com/</a> for more information.<br /><br />The second is from the United States with books.  I heard about it via Twitter<br />"RT @<a href="http://twitter.com/iEatWordsTweets" rel="self" title="http://twitter.com/iEatWordsTweets">iEatWordsTweets</a>: @<a href="http://twitter.com/cassieclare" rel="self" title="http://twitter.com/cassieclare">cassieclare</a> Hi Cassie! Would you please help us raise awareness for our Books for Kids charity? <a href="http://bit.ly/e8ACRT" rel="self" title="http://bit.ly/e8ACRT">http://bit.ly/e8ACRT</a>"<br />The Phoenix Children's Hospital and Scottish Rite Hospital for terminally ill children are asking for help towards buying brand new books for children.<br />Please see <a href="http://www.ieatwords.net/2011/02/books-for-kids-lets-give-back.html" rel="self" title="http://www.ieatwords.net/2011/02/books-for-kids-lets-give-back.html">http://www.ieatwords.net/2011/02/books-for-kids-lets-give-back.html</a> for more information.<br /></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-383" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Captain Jack or Captain Kidd?</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Thursday, 06 January 2011 </div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="" src="page73_blog_entry383_1.jpg" width="40" height="40" /></div>Captain Jack Sparrow's costume is going to be on show at the Museum of London in Docklands from 20th May to 30th October according to a clipping from the evening standard I was given.  The exhibition is about a pirate who was executed in 1701 for piracy and murder in Wapping.  Like the fictional character Captain Jack, Captain Kidd operated out of the Caribbean and had dealings with the East India company.  As well as Johnny Depp's costume there will be a real pirate flag, an eighteenth century cannon and an outfit from Vivienne Westwood's Pirate Collection.<br /></div></div>
	</div>
	
	 

